The paper deals with the automated verification of security protocols, which is a topic that falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also involves formal modeling and process calculus, which are topics that fall under the category of logic in computer science (cs.LO). The use of trusted computing platforms and protected hardware such as TPM also suggests that the paper may fall under the category of software engineering (cs.SE). The introduction of new equational theories for representing TPM specific platform states and dynamically loaded programs suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of programming languages (cs.PL). Finally, the paper deals with the verification of protocols running in a dynamic root of trust context, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of systems and control (cs.SY).
